{
  "topicId": "derangements-nothing-is-in-its-right-place",
  "mcqs": [
    {
      "id": "mcq-1",
      "question": "What is the value of D(6)?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "265"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "264"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "266"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "260"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "265",
      "explanation": "Using recurrence: D(6) = 5 × [D(5)+D(4)] = 5 × [44+9] = 5 × 53 = 265",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-2",
      "question": "The derangement of n objects is also known as:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Superfactorial"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "Subfactorial"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Hyperfactorial"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Mega factorial"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Subfactorial",
      "explanation": "Derangements are denoted by !n, which is called subfactorial. It represents n! minus the permutations with at least one fixed point.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-3",
      "question": "What is D(0) equal to?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "0"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "1"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "2"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Undefined"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "1",
      "explanation": "By convention, D(0) = 1. The empty permutation is considered a derangement since there are no elements to be in their original position.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-4",
      "question": "The limit of D(n)/n! as n → ∞ is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "1/e"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "e"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "1"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "0"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "1/e",
      "explanation": "Using the inclusion-exclusion formula, D(n)/n! approaches 1 - 1/1! + 1/2! - ... = 1/e ≈ 0.3679",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-5",
      "question": "Which mathematician first studied derangements?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Euler"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "Bernoulli"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Gauss"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Newton"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Bernoulli",
      "explanation": "The Swiss mathematician Jacob Bernoulli is credited with first studying the derangement problem, though Euler also contributed significantly.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-6",
      "question": "What is the recurrence relation for derangements?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "D(n) = n × D(n-1)"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "D(n) = (n-1) × D(n-2)"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "D(n) = (n-1)[D(n-1) + D(n-2)]"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "D(n) = n![D(n-1) + D(n-2)]"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "D(n) = (n-1)[D(n-1) + D(n-2)]",
      "explanation": "This recurrence is derived using inclusion-exclusion principle. For n ≥ 2, D(n) = (n-1)[D(n-1) + D(n-2)]",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-7",
      "question": "In the hat-check problem with 4 people, the probability that nobody gets their own hat is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "9/24"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "8/24"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "7/24"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "10/24"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "9/24",
      "explanation": "There are 4! = 24 total permutations and D(4) = 9 derangements. So probability = 9/24 = 3/8",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-8",
      "question": "What is D(1)?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "0"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "1"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "2"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "-1"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "0",
      "explanation": "With only one object, it must remain in its original position, so there are no possible derangements.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-9",
      "question": "The inclusion-exclusion formula for D(n) is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "n! × Σ(-1)^k/k!"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "n! × Σ(1)^k/k!"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "n × D(n-1)"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "n! - D(n-1)"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "n! × Σ(-1)^k/k!",
      "explanation": "Using inclusion-exclusion, D(n) = n! × [1 - 1/1! + 1/2! - 1/3! + ... + (-1)^n/n!]",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-10",
      "question": "For n ≥ 1, D(n) is always:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Even"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "Odd"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Prime"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Divisible by n"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Even",
      "explanation": "For n ≥ 2, D(n) is always even. This can be proven using the recurrence relation D(n) = (n-1)[D(n-1) + D(n-2)].",
      "difficulty": "hard"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-11",
      "question": "What is the value of D(3)?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "1"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "2"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "3"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "4"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "2",
      "explanation": "The derangements of (1,2,3) are (2,3,1) and (3,1,2). Both have no element in its original position.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-12",
      "question": "If D(n) = 44, then n equals:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "4"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "5"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "6"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "7"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "5",
      "explanation": "D(5) = 44. Using recurrence: D(5) = 4 × [D(4)+D(3)] = 4 × [9+2] = 44",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-13",
      "question": "The expected number of fixed points in a random permutation of n elements is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "0"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "1"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "n"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "1/e"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "1",
      "explanation": "Each element has probability 1/n of being a fixed point. By linearity of expectation, the expected number is n × (1/n) = 1.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
